SIMPLE: indorsement
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indorsement
<hw>In*dorse"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Indorse</er>; cf. <er>Endorsement</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>endorsement</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of writing on the back of a note, bill, or
other written instrument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is written on the back of a note, bill,
or other paper, as a name, an order for, or a receipt of, payment, or
the return of an officer, etc.; a writing, usually upon the back, but
sometimes on the face, of a negotiable instrument, by which the property
therein is assigned and transferred.</def> <rj><au>Story. Byles.
Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Sanction, support, or approval; <as>as, the
<ex>indorsement</ex> of a rumor, an opinion, a course,
conduct</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Blank indorsement</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Blank</er>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Indorsor</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Indorser</ent>⟦br⟧
